  "title": "Orders of Magnitude",
  "body": " Orders of Magnitude    Demonstrate an understanding of the magnitude of real numbers represented in many forms (fractions, decimals, scientific notation, square roots of numbers) by ordering and comparing them in mathematical and real-world contexts.     A large economic and political concern is the federal deficit, the amount of money spent by the federal government in excess of revenue collected annually. The federal budget deficit for 2015 was approximately $435 billion. The federal debt is the accumulated deficits from all years, and in 2015 was about $18.1 trillion.  It is difficult to understand just how big a billion or a trillion is. Here is a way to help you think about it.     1 million  = 1,000 1,000  = 1,000,000       1 billion  = 1,000 1,000 1,000  = 1,000,000,000       1 trillion  = 1,000 1,000 1,000 1,000  = 1,000,000,000,000         U.S. National Debt from 1990-2020.   Source: US Department of the Treasury. (September 30, 2021). Public debt of the United States from 1990 to 2021 (in billion U.S. dollars) [Graph]. In Statista. Retrieved April 18, 2022, from       Thousand, Million, Billion, and Trillion     What is a simpler way to express 2000 billion dollars?    Imagine a stack of 1,000 one-dollar bills, which is about 4.3 inches tall. Imagine combining 1,000 stacks of 1,000 one-dollar bills. How much money is in the stack, and how tall (in feet) would it be?    Try to come up with a well-known or common thing that is basically the same height or length as your answer to . Feel free to use the internet.    Now imagine combining 1000 stacks like the one above in . How much money is in the stack, and how tall (in miles) would it be?    Try to come up with a well-known or common thing that is basically the same height or length as your answer to . Feel free to use the internet.    Now imagine combining 1000 stacks like the one above in . How much money is in the stack, and how tall (in miles) would it be?    Since the circumference of the earth is a litte less then 25,000 miles, how many times would this stack from go around the world?    Your friends are discussing an entertainment strike (actor's guild, baseball, hockey, whatever your friends care about most) where the professionals, who are generally millionaires, are against the owners, who are generaly billionaires. Try to to explain the difference between a million and a billion in a simple but also insightful way to your friends.       Scientific Notation   You saw that 1 billion can be written as 1,000,000,000 or represented as . How would 2 billion be represented? Since 2 billion is 2 times 1 billion, then 2 billion can be written as . Writing numbers in this way is called scientific notation. Scientific notation is used primarily for writing very large numbers and very small numbers. In this lesson, we will focus on large numbers.  The form for scientific notation is where . The exponent equals the number of decimal places between the location of the decimal in the number as written in standard notation and the number written in scientific notation.  For example, if the number 500 were to be written in scientific notation, it could be thought of as or which is equal to . The decimal point has been moved 2 places which corresponds to the exponent of 2.  Likewise, if the number 4300 were to be written in scientific notation, it could be thought of as or which is equal to . The decimal point has been moved 3 places (between 4300. and 4.3) which corresponds to the exponent of 3.     Write the numbers below in both standard notation and scientific notation.      Words  Standard Notation  Scientific Notation    four hundred          twenty three thousand          7.2 million              The table below contains the national deficit and national debt for various years. Write the number in both standard notation and scientific notation.      Words  Standard Notation  Scientific Notation    1965 deficit: $1.41 billion          2009 deficit: $1412.69 billion          2014 deficit: $484.6 billion          2014 debt: $18.2 trillion                  Comparing the Sizes of Numbers   One of the skills you will learn in this course is how to write quantitative information. A writing principle that you will use throughout the course is given below followed by the questions below, which give you examples of how to use this principle.   Writing Principle: Use specific and complete information. The reader should understand what you are trying to say even if they have not read the question or writing prompt. This includes    information about context, and  quantitative information       A headline in 2014 read “Scott vetoes $69 million in $77-billion state budget”. Is the $69 million a small or large portion of the total state budget? The following four statements are all correct. Which statement provides the best description, based on the writing principle?  The portion vetoed is a very small part of the entire state budget.  $69 million is about a thousandth of $77 billion.  The $69 million vetoed is a very small part of the entire state budget of $77 billion.  The $69 million that was vetoed is about one tenth of one percent of the total $77 billion state budget.      The federal budget in 2012 included $471 billion for Medicare and $47 billion for International Affairs. Complete the statement below that compares the two quantities.  The budget of $471 billion for Medicare is about times larger than the $47 billion budget for International Affairs.      Using the writing principle above, in a full sentence compare the 2009 deficit and the 2014 deficit from exercise 9.        Estimate, then Calculate   For each situation below, describe your estimation strategy for each situation. Then estimate without a calculator . Then and only then go back use a calculator to refine your estimate.     About 3 million working people in the U.S. make at or below the federal minimum wage of $7.25 per hour. Estimate the amount of money needed per year to raise their wages to $15 per hour.    The amount of money needed to buy everyone in your state a box of Girl Scout cookies.    The amount of money needed to send all graduating high school seniors in the United States to college for four years.    If the U.S. national debt was $22 trillion in 2019, and was evenly divided among the people living in the United States, how much would each person's share be?    If the U.S. budget is about $4.1 trillion, estimate the percentage of the budget which would be needed to pay for your estimate in above.       "
