  "type": "Activity",
  "number": "3.4.1",
  "title": "",
  "body": "     Sam has a student loan of $30,000 at a fixed APR of 4.45%. If he wants to pay it off in 15 years, how much would he pay per month?    How much would Sam pay in total?    What percentage of the total was paid toward the loan amount of $30,000 and what percentage was paid toward interest?           =PMT(0.0445\/12, 15*12, 30000, 0)   = $228.73  They would need to pay $228.73 per month for 15 years.     =$228.73*15*12   = $41,171.40  They would pay a total of $41,171.40 for the loan.     Percentage toward the principal:   =$30,000\/41,171.40   ≈73%  About 73% of the total was paid toward the principal. That means about 27% was paid in interest.       "
